The indigenous '''Gran Chaco people''' consist of approximately thirty-five tribal groups in the [[Gran Chaco]] of South America.  Because, like the [[Great Plains|Great Plains of North America]], the terrain lent itself to a [[nomad]]ic lifestyle, there is little to no archaeological evidence of their prehistoric occupation.  Contributing to this near-absence of archaeological data is the lack of suitable raw material for stone tools or permanent construction and soil conditions that are not conducive to the preservation of organic material.<ref>{{harvnb|Combes|Villar|Lowrey|2009|p=71}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|author1=Calandra, Horacio Adolfo  |author2=Salceda, Susana Alicia|year=2008 |chapter=Cambio y continuidad en el Gran Chaco: De las historias étnicas a la prehistoria|editor=Braunstein, José |editor2=Meichtry, Norma C.|title=Liderazgo, representatividad y control social en el Gran Chaco|location=Corrientes, Argentina|publisher=Universidad Nacional del Nordeste|pages=31–38, pages&nbsp;32&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;33|isbn=978-950-656-116-1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ISzI6iJoKGYC&pg=PA31}}</ref>

==Geography==
The actual cultural area of the Gran Chaco peoples differs from that of the geographic Gran Chaco.  The northwestern boundary of the cultural area is the [[Parapetí River]] and the marshes of the Bañados de Izozog depression, beyond which were the lands of the cultural unrelated [[Chané people|Chané]] and [[Chiriguano]]. The cultural boundaries have not been static, even during historical times.  In the late 17th century the area expanded to the east across the [[Paraguay River]], when the [[Mbayá]] invaded the lands between the [[Apa River]] and the [[Miranda River]] in [[Mato Grosso do Sul]] province in Brazil.<ref>{{harvnb|Métraux|1946|p=[http://ia600401.us.archive.org/BookReader/BookReaderImages.php?id=bulletin14311946smit&itemPath=%2F25%2Fitems%2Fbulletin14311946smit&server=ia600401.us.archive.org&page=n264_w292 197]}}</ref>

==Languages==
The tribal groups of the Gran Chaco fall into six [[Language family|language families]]:<ref>{{harvnb|Combes|Villar|Lowrey|2009|p=69}}</ref>
# [[Matacoan languages]] or Mataco-maká ([[Wichí languages]], [[Chorote languages]], [[Nivaclé language]]s and the [[Maká language]])
# [[Guaicuruan languages]] 
# [[Lule–Vilela languages]]
# [[Mascoian languages]]
# [[Zamucoan languages]]
# [[Tupi–Guarani languages]]

